    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-12-04T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-12-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="623"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d623">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.0146/918</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 221</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-12-04">December 4,
                            1941</date>.<lb/>[Received August 26, 1942.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer to the Department’s
                    telegraphic instruction no. 267 of November 14, 1941, 2 p.m. to the Embassy at
                    Chungking in regard to the withdrawal of the United States Marine Forces in
                    North China…</p>
                <p>The Department will notice that in notifying the Senior Ambassador of the
                    withdrawal, I have used the word “temporary”. While the reservation of rights
                    under the Final Protocol of November [<hi rend="italic">September</hi>] 7, 1901
                    in itself would doubtless serve as sufficient basis for any desired return of
                    American forces in North China so long as the Protocol is in force, I
                    nevertheless deemed it advisable at the risk of redundancy, to provide
                    specifically for any desired return of the troops by referring to their
                    withdrawal as “temporary” and I trust my action will meet with the Department’s
                    approval.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>For the Ambassador: <lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Richard</hi> P. <hi rend="smallcaps">Butrick</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Counselor of Embassy</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
